\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Worker-Side Model of Discrimination
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Employers learn about worker's ability and motivation towards employer's
 group identity from the worker's group identity and use this information
 to evaluate the quality of the worker's output.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Workers
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Consider a worker who has 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
observable group identity 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{w}\in\{B,W\}$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
observable employer's group identity 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{e}\in\{B,W\}$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
unobservable ability 
\begin_inset Formula $a\sim N(\mu_{r_{w}},1/\tau_{a})$
\end_inset

 with mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{r_{w}}\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and precision 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{a}>0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
unobservable motivation towards the employer's group 
\begin_inset Formula $m\sim N(\zeta_{r_{w}}^{r_{e}},1/\tau_{m})$
\end_inset

 with mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{r_{w}}^{r_{e}}\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and precision 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{m}>0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The worker completes a task with quality 
\begin_inset Formula $q=a+m+\epsilon$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon\sim N(0,1/\tau_{\epsilon})$
\end_inset

 is a random shock with precision 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{\epsilon}>1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Higher ability and higher motivation towards the employer's group generates
 higher expected quality.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Employers
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
An employer evaluates the worker's performance on the task and reports evaluatio
n of 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 can be considered as the reward, promotion, decision to not fire the worker
 etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Before evaluating the task, the employer observes the worker's identity
 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{w}$
\end_inset

 and a signal 
\begin_inset Formula $s=q+\eta$
\end_inset

 of the quality of the task where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\sim N(0,1/\tau_{\eta})$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{\eta}>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Lower precision allows for greater uncertainty in the underlying quality,
 conditional on the signal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{\eta}$
\end_inset

 can be interpreted as the amount of subjectivity in judgment involved in
 the evaluation of the quality, with lower precision implying greater subjectivi
ty.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Evaluation strategy by employer of group 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{e}$
\end_inset

 is a mapping from the worker's group identity 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{w}$
\end_inset

 and a signal 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 to the evaluation 
\begin_inset Formula $v(r_{e},r_{w},s)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Payoffs
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
An employer's payoff depends on the quality of the task and the group identity
 of the worker.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Employer of group 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{e}$
\end_inset

 receives a payoff of 
\begin_inset Formula $-(v-(q-c_{r_{w}}^{r_{e}}))^{2}$
\end_inset

 from giving evaluation 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 on a task of quality 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 from a worker of group 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{w}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{r_{w}}^{r_{e}}$
\end_inset

is a taste parameter.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Partialities
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
An employer is partial towards one group if she favors that group, 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
either directly through preferences, which we refer to as 
\series bold
preference-based partiality
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
a white employer has preference based partiality towards white workers if
 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{B}^{W}>0$
\end_inset

.
 Normalizing 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{W}^{W}=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
or indirectly through her belief about the distribution of ability and motivatio
n which we refer to as 
\series bold
belief-based partiality
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
a white employer has belief based partiality towards white workers if 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mu}_{W}>\hat{\mu}_{B}$
\end_inset

 or 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\zeta}_{W}^{W}>\hat{\zeta}_{B}^{W}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
This partiality if unbiased if 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mu}_{W}=\mu_{W}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mu}_{B}=\mu_{B}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\zeta}_{W}^{W}=\zeta_{W}^{W}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\zeta}_{B}^{W}=\zeta_{B}^{W}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Discrimination
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Discrimination is the disparate evaluation of workers based on the group
 to which the worker belongs, rather than on individual attributes, i.e.
 signal.
 In contrast to partiality, which is a property of the primitives of the
 model (preferences, beliefs), discrimination is a property of behavior.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D(W,s)\equiv v(W,W,s)-v(W,B,s)
\]

\end_inset

denote the difference between a white's and black's evaluation by the white
 employer at signal s.
 Analogously 
\begin_inset Formula $D(B,s)\equiv v(B,W,s)-v(B,B,s)$
\end_inset

 denote the difference between a white and black's worker's evaluation by
 the black employer at signal 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A black (white) worker faces discrimination by white employer at signal
 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $D(W,s)>0$
\end_inset

 (
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $D(W,s)<0$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A black (white) worker faces discrimination by black employer at signal
 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $D(B,s)>0$
\end_inset

 (
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $D(B,s)<0$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Heterogeneous Employers
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Suppose each type of employer is characterized by a tuple 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta^{W}=(\hat{\mu}_{B}^{\theta},\hat{\mu}_{W}^{\theta},\hat{\zeta}_{B}^{r_{e}},\hat{\zeta}_{W}^{r_{e}},c_{B}^{r_{e}},\hat{\pi}^{\theta})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
This specifies beliefs about the mean ability of black and white workers,
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
beliefs about mean motivation of black and white workers towards the employer's
 race, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
a taste parameter for blacks, and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
a belief about the type distribution of other employers, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\pi}^{\theta}\in\Delta(\Theta)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta$
\end_inset

 denotes the set of employer types, which we assume to be finite.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\in\Delta(\Theta)$
\end_inset

 denote the true measure over employer types.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Aggregation
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
There is aggregate preference based partiality towards white workers by
 white employers if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E[c_{B}^{W}]>0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There is aggregate belief based partiality towards white workers by white
 employers if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{\pi}[\hat{\mu}_{W}]>E_{\pi}[\hat{\mu}_{B}]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
or 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{\pi}[\hat{\zeta}_{W}^{r_{e}}]>E_{\pi}[\hat{\zeta}_{B}^{r_{e}}]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

